JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) is a lightweight data-interchange format that is easy for humans to read and write, and easy for machines to parse and generate. It is text-based and language-independent, but it uses conventions familiar to programmers of C-family languages (C, C#, Java, JavaScript, etc.).

Key Features:
Structure: JSON is built on two structures:

Objects: Collections of key-value pairs enclosed in {}.

Arrays: Ordered lists of values enclosed in [].

Data Types: Supports strings, numbers, booleans, null, objects, and arrays.

Usage in Web Development:

Widely used for client-server communication.

Commonly returned by APIs and MVC controllers.

Easily parsed by JavaScript using JSON.parse() and serialized using JSON.stringify().

Advantages:

Lightweight compared to XML.

Human-readable and easy to debug.

Supported natively in JavaScript and most modern languages.

In ASP.NET MVC:

Controllers often return JSON using JsonResult.

Useful for AJAX calls where you want to update part of a page without full reload.

Integrates seamlessly with DataTables for dynamic data binding.

📝 25 Interview-Style Q&A (Detailed)
JSON Return in MVC Controller
Q: How do you return JSON from an MVC controller?
A: Use JsonResult. Example:

csharp
public JsonResult GetData() {
    var data = new { Name = "Manoranjan", Age = 25 };
    return Json(data, JsonRequestBehavior.AllowGet);
}
This serializes the object into JSON and sends it to the client.

Q: Why do we use JsonRequestBehavior.AllowGet?
A: By default, MVC blocks GET requests for JSON to prevent sensitive data exposure. AllowGet explicitly permits GET requests, useful for safe data like dropdown lists.

Q: What happens if you don’t use AllowGet in a GET request?
A: MVC throws an exception: “This request has been blocked because sensitive information could be disclosed to third-party websites…”.

Q: How do you return a list of objects as JSON?
A: Serialize collections:

csharp
return Json(myList, JsonRequestBehavior.AllowGet);
The client receives an array of JSON objects.

Q: Can you customize JSON serialization in MVC?
A: Yes, by using JsonResult with custom JsonSerializerSettings (e.g., camelCase, ignoring nulls).

Page Refresh & isRefresh
Q: What is the difference between a full page refresh and partial refresh?
A: Full refresh reloads the entire HTML, CSS, JS, and data. Partial refresh (AJAX) updates only a section, improving performance and user experience.

Q: How can you detect if a page is refreshed in JavaScript?
A: Use performance.navigation.type.

javascript
if (performance.navigation.type === performance.navigation.TYPE_RELOAD) {
    console.log("Page was refreshed");
}
Q: What is isRefresh in MVC context?
A: It’s a flag developers use to detect if the request is due to a page reload. For example, storing a value in TempData or session and checking it on reload.

Q: How do you prevent duplicate form submissions on refresh?
A: Use PRG (Post-Redirect-Get) pattern. After form submission, redirect to a GET action, so refresh doesn’t resubmit.

Q: How can you force a page refresh after JSON data update?
A: Use JavaScript:

javascript
location.reload();
Or refresh only a section using AJAX.

DataTables Refresh
Q: How do you bind JSON data to a DataTable?
A:

javascript
$('#myTable').DataTable({
    ajax: '/Controller/GetData',
    columns: [
        { data: 'Name' },
        { data: 'Age' }
    ]
});
Q: How do you refresh a DataTable without reloading the page?
A:

javascript
var table = $('#myTable').DataTable();
table.ajax.reload();
Q: What is the difference between ajax.reload() and draw() in DataTables?
A: ajax.reload() fetches new data from the server. draw() redraws the table with existing data.

Q: How do you refresh DataTable after inserting new data?
A: Call table.ajax.reload() inside the AJAX success callback after saving data.

Q: How do you handle server-side pagination with DataTables?
A: Configure DataTables with serverSide: true and return JSON with recordsTotal, recordsFiltered, and data.

Advanced JSON + MVC + Refresh Scenarios
Q: How do you return JSON with status codes in MVC?
A: Use Json(new { success = true, message = "Saved" }). The client checks success.

Q: How do you refresh only a div with JSON data?
A: Use jQuery AJAX:

javascript
$.getJSON('/Controller/GetData', function(data) {
    $('#myDiv').html(data.Name);
});
Q: How do you handle JSON errors in MVC?
A: Wrap in try-catch and return JSON with error message:

csharp
return Json(new { success = false, error = ex.Message });
Q: How do you refresh DataTable when filters change?
A: Pass parameters in AJAX call:

javascript
table.ajax.url('/Controller/GetData?filter=value').load();
Q: How do you avoid caching issues with JSON refresh?
A: Append timestamp to URL:

javascript
table.ajax.url('/Controller/GetData?t=' + new Date().getTime()).load();
Practical Interview-Oriented Questions
Q: Explain how JSON helps avoid full page reloads.
A: JSON allows partial updates via AJAX, so only data changes, not the entire page. This improves performance.

Q: How do you debug JSON issues in MVC?
A: Use browser dev tools → Network tab → Inspect JSON response. Also log server-side serialization.

Q: How do you refresh DataTable after deleting a row?
A: Perform delete via AJAX, then call table.ajax.reload() to fetch updated data.

Q: How do you handle large JSON data in DataTables?
A: Use server-side processing (serverSide: true) to fetch only required rows per page.

Q: How do you ensure DataTable refresh doesn’t break sorting/pagination?
A: Use table.ajax.reload(null, false) to refresh data but retain current page and sort order.
